INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '736e0504-8904-40b5-8d79-f47dc11b2477',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elixir Memory Management — Per-Process GC, Binary Heaps, and the Leak You're Missing$escape$,
  $escape$Elixir's memory model differs fundamentally from Rust's ownership model and traditional stop-the-world GC languages. The BEAM gives every process its own isolated heap — GC runs per-process, not globally. When a process dies, its heap is reclaimed instantly with zero GC pause. Immutability replaces ownership: since data never mutates, the VM avoids write barriers entirely. Sending a message between processes deep-copies data into the receiver's heap — no shared mutable state, ever.

Binaries break this rule. Large binaries (>64 bytes) live on a shared binary heap, reference-counted across processes. Small binaries (≤64 bytes) are copied inline. The dangerous edge case: a sub-binary created with binary pattern matching holds a reference to the full parent binary. If a long-lived process holds even a 4-byte slice of a 50 MB binary, that entire 50 MB stays alive. `:erlang.process_info(pid, :binary)` exposes exactly which binaries a process references and their ref counts — your first diagnostic call when a BEAM node's memory climbs without obvious cause.

Each process starts with a small heap (~1.8 KB) that grows on demand, making millions of concurrent processes practical without upfront allocation cost.$escape$,
  $escape$# Per-process GC: each process owns its heap
pid = spawn(fn ->
  _data = Enum.to_list(1..50_000)
  :timer.sleep(:infinity)
end)

{:memory, bytes} = :erlang.process_info(pid, :memory)
IO.puts("Process heap: #{div(bytes, 1024)} KB")

# Sub-binary reference pins the entire parent binary in memory
big_bin = String.duplicate("x", 256)  # goes to shared binary heap (>64 bytes)
<<sub::binary-size(4), _::binary>> = big_bin

{:binary, refs} = :erlang.process_info(self(), :binary)
# [{ref_id, size_bytes, ref_count}] — sub still holds big_bin alive
IO.inspect(refs, label: "binary refs")$escape$,
  $escape$elixir$escape$,
