INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b789c972-eb3b-45f2-bc59-33f2a52ad887',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elixir Error Handling — {:ok}/{:error} Tuples vs Exceptions$escape$,
  $escape$Elixir draws a hard line: {:ok, value} / {:error, reason} tuples for expected failures, exceptions for programmer errors or truly unrecoverable states. The standard library enforces this via bang variants — File.read/1 returns {:error, :enoent}, File.read!/1 raises RuntimeError. Use the non-bang form whenever failure is a normal branch of your logic.

The real power is with/1, which short-circuits an {:error, _} anywhere in a pipeline without nested case blocks. Each clause pattern-matches on {:ok, val}; the else block handles specific error shapes. This keeps the happy path linear and error handling explicit at the boundary.

Raise exceptions (raise MyApp.NotFoundError) only for contract violations — bad arguments, missing config, or states your code should never reach. rescue is rare in production Elixir; let it crash and let supervisors restart. For domain errors propagating across process boundaries, prefer tagged tuples: {:error, {:validation, changeset}} gives callers enough structure to branch on without parsing exception messages.$escape$,
  $escape$defmodule UserOnboarding do
  def call(user_id) do
    with {:ok, user} <- Accounts.fetch_user(user_id),
         {:ok, plan} <- Billing.create_trial(user),
         {:ok, _mail} <- Mailer.send_welcome(user) do
      {:ok, %{user: user, plan: plan}}
    else
      {:error, :not_found} -> {:error, "User #{user_id} not found"}
      {:error, :payment_gateway_down} -> {:error, "Retry later"}
      {:error, reason} -> {:error, reason}
    end
  end
end$escape$,
  $escape$elixir$escape$,
