INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a16f1de6-9f5a-4032-be6b-5d6c87a2e50d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elixir Testing with ExUnit — Doctests, Async, and the `assert` Philosophy$escape$,
  $escape$Elixir ships ExUnit in the standard library — no Hex package needed. The test runner is invoked via `mix test`, and parallelism is opt-in per module with `use ExUnit.Case, async: true`. Modules with no shared mutable state (the norm in Elixir) should always set `async: true`.

ExUnit's `assert` is a macro, not a function. It pattern-matches and inspects the AST to produce rich diffs on failure — `assert result == {:ok, 42}` prints exactly what differed, not a generic "assertion failed".

Elixir's killer testing feature is doctests: `doctest MyModule` parses `iex>` examples from `@doc` strings and runs them as tests. This enforces living documentation — if your docs lie, CI fails.

For side-effectful code, use `setup` callbacks with `on_exit` to clean up. Avoid mocking modules via third-party libraries by default; prefer passing dependencies as arguments (higher-order functions or behaviours) so tests swap implementations without monkey-patching.$escape$,
  $escape$defmodule MathTest do
  use ExUnit.Case, async: true
  doctest Math

  describe "divide/2" do
    test "returns {:ok, result} on success" do
      assert Math.divide(10, 2) == {:ok, 5.0}
    end

    test "returns {:error, :division_by_zero}" do
      assert Math.divide(10, 0) == {:error, :division_by_zero}
    end
  end
end$escape$,
  $escape$elixir$escape$,
