INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b71a2f89-d6f2-4aa2-b56c-d6e2618434b9',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elixir Code Quality — Enforcing Style with mix format, Credo, and Idiomatic Patterns$escape$,
  $escape$Elixir ships with `mix format` out of the box — run it in CI with `mix format --check-formatted` to fail builds on unformatted code. Configure it in `.formatter.exs`, including `inputs` globs and `import_deps` for libraries like Ecto or Phoenix that export their own formatter plugins.

For deeper static analysis, Credo (`mix credo --strict`) flags anti-patterns specific to Elixir: deeply nested `case` blocks that should use `with`, functions exceeding complexity thresholds, and missing `@moduledoc` attributes. Add `# credo:disable-for-next-line` sparingly — prefer fixing the root issue.

The most impactful idiomatic shift is replacing defensive `if/else` chains with multi-clause function heads and guard clauses. Credo's `Credo.Check.Refactor.CondStatements` and `Credo.Check.Warning.BoolOperationOnSameValues` catches these automatically. For type safety without a full type system, add `@spec` annotations and run Dialyzer via Dialyxir (`mix dialyzer`) — it catches mismatched return types across module boundaries that Credo misses entirely. Wire all three into GitHub Actions as separate steps so failures are attributed to the right tool.$escape$,
  $escape$# .formatter.exs
[
  inputs: ["{mix,.formatter}.exs", "{config,lib,test}/**/*.{ex,exs}"],
  import_deps: [:ecto, :phoenix]
]

# Idiomatic: multi-clause over nested case
# Bad
def process(user) do
  case user.active do
    true -> case user.role do
      :admin -> {:ok, :full_access}
      _ -> {:ok, :limited}
    end
    false -> {:error, :inactive}
  end
end

# Good
def process(%{active: false}), do: {:error, :inactive}
def process(%{active: true, role: :admin}), do: {:ok, :full_access}
def process(%{active: true}), do: {:ok, :limited}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
