INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cd89f9a4-1575-433f-b348-b6d9976e4368',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elixir OTP — How Supervisors and GenServers Make Your System Fault-Tolerant$escape$,
  $escape$Elixir's OTP framework isn't just a library — it's a battle-tested concurrency model built on the Actor pattern. Every GenServer is an isolated process with its own heap, mailbox, and state. When it crashes, it takes nothing else down with it. Supervisors sit above these processes and define restart strategies: `:one_for_one` restarts only the failed child, `:one_for_all` restarts every sibling, and `:rest_for_one` restarts the failed child and all children started after it.

The key insight: you don't write defensive code to prevent crashes — you let processes crash and let supervisors recover them. This is the "let it crash" philosophy. Combined with supervision trees, you get self-healing systems without try/catch sprawl.

A GenServer holds state via `handle_call/3` and `handle_cast/2`. `call` is synchronous (blocks the caller), `cast` is fire-and-forget. Use `call` when you need a return value; `cast` for side effects. State lives in the return tuple — no mutable variables, no shared memory. Process isolation is the unit of fault tolerance in Elixir.$escape$,
  $escape$defmodule Counter do
  use GenServer

  def start_link(initial \\ 0),
    do: GenServer.start_link(__MODULE__, initial, name: __MODULE__)

  def increment, do: GenServer.cast(__MODULE__, :inc)
  def value,     do: GenServer.call(__MODULE__, :get)

  @impl true
  def init(count), do: {:ok, count}

  @impl true
  def handle_cast(:inc, count), do: {:noreply, count + 1}

  @impl true
  def handle_call(:get, _from, count), do: {:reply, count, count}
end$escape$,
  $escape$elixir$escape$,
