INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '762614ab-e23a-4e79-86a6-06bb1f9fd04d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Elixir Production Monitoring — Scheduler Utilization, Per-Process GC, and recon$escape$,
  $escape$BEAM's GC model is per-process — each process owns its heap and collects independently. There's no global stop-the-world pause, but individual processes can stall under heap pressure. Understanding this distinction is critical before reaching for profiling tools.

Track scheduler utilization before CPU. A saturated run queue (`:erlang.statistics(:run_queue)`) is often the real bottleneck. Enable `:scheduler_wall_time` at boot via `:erlang.system_flag(:scheduler_wall_time, true)` to get accurate wall-time ratios per scheduler.

For memory, `:erlang.memory/0` returns a breakdown across `:processes`, `:atom`, `:binary`, `:ets`, and `:code`. Binary leaks are a common surprise — binaries over 64 bytes live on the shared heap, not the process heap, so per-process GC won't reclaim them. Watch `:erlang.memory(:binary)` under sustained load.

In production, use `recon` for safe runtime inspection. `:recon.proc_count(:memory, 5)` identifies the top five memory consumers without risking node instability. Pipe BEAM VM metrics into Prometheus via `PromEx`, which hooks directly into `:telemetry` and ships pre-built BEAM dashboards for Grafana.$escape$,
  $escape$:erlang.system_flag(:scheduler_wall_time, true)

# Scheduler wall-time: {scheduler_id, active_time, total_time}
schedulers = :erlang.statistics(:scheduler_wall_time)
IO.inspect(schedulers, label: "scheduler utilization")

# GC stats: {number_of_gcs, words_reclaimed, 0}
{gcs, words, _} = :erlang.statistics(:garbage_collection)
IO.puts("GCs: #{gcs}, words reclaimed: #{words}")

# Memory breakdown
:erlang.memory()
|> Keyword.take([:processes, :binary, :ets])
|> IO.inspect(label: "memory bytes")

# Top 5 processes by memory — safe in prod
:recon.proc_count(:memory, 5)$escape$,
  $escape$elixir$escape$,
